===Etymology===
From earlier {{m|en|risque}}, from {{bor|en|frm|risque}}, from {{der|en|it|risco|t=risk}} (modern {{cog|it|rischio}}) and {{m|it|rischiare|t=to run into danger}}. 
{{rel-top|speculation on earlier roots}}
Most dictionaries consider the etymology of these Italian terms uncertain, but some suggest they perhaps come from {{der|en|VL.|*resicum||that which cuts, rock, crag}} (> {{cog|ML.|resicu}}), from {{der|en|la|resecō||cut off, loose, curtail|pos=verb}}, in the sense of that which is a danger to boating or shipping; or from {{der|en|grc|ῥιζικόν||root, radical, hazard}}.

A few dictionaries express more certainty. Collins says the Italian {{m|it|risco}} comes from {{der|en|grc|ῥίζα||cliff}} due to the hazards of sailing along rocky coasts. The American Heritage says it probably comes from {{der|en|gkm|ῥιζικό|ῥιζικό, ριζικό|t=sustenance obtained by a soldier through his own initiative, fortune}}, from {{der|en|ar|رِزْق|tr=rizq|t=sustenance, that which God allots}}, from {{der|en|syc|ܪܙܩܐ|ܪܘܙܝܩܐ ,ܪܙܩܐ|tr=rezqā, rōzīqā|t=daily ration}}, from {{der|en|pal|tr=rōčig}}, from {{der|en|pal|tr=rōč|t=day}}, from {{der|en|peo|tr=*raučah-}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*lewk-}}.

Cognate with Spanish {{m|es|riesgo}}, Portuguese {{m|pt|risco}}
